“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, a country without a coastline, hopes the court will open the way to the Pacific
Sailors are patrolling a rig-covered naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings raise a sea-blue flag.
Marine bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are decorated with the motto: “We have a right to the sea.
It is our duty to recover it.”
The entire inland state of Bolivia still has fresh memories of the coastline they lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century, and the country longs to be able to sail the Pacific once again.
These hopes are perhaps greater than they have been in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice on 1 October after five years of deliberation.
“Bolivia has drive, community spirit and serenity, and of course awaits the result with a positive attitude,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the ruling of the International Court of Justice on the big screen in many different places in the country, hoping that the Hague court will give its ruling in favor of Bolivia’s claim that Chile – after decades of sporadic negotiations – is committed to negotiating to give Bolivia its own outlet to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic native president – who is facing a controversial re-election campaign next year – has also invested heavily in Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to a return to the Pacific,” he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to take Bolivia’s side, and that very little would change if it did.
The UN agency, as the team in the Netherlands, has no authority to allow them to give away Chilean lands, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The ruling of the International Court of Justice comes just six months after the last arguments were heard, suggesting that the case “was not complicated,” according to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And rather than promoting Bolivia’s cause, the past four years may have actually made things worse.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
She believes that Morales's antagonistic rhetoric has depleted any remaining goodwill on Chile's part.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at one point or another, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the matter afterwards.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative at The Hague, rejected the theory that the court’s decision came unusually quickly.
On Monday, Bolivia will provide an “extraordinary opportunity to open up a new generation of relations with Chile” and the opportunity to “put an end to 139 years of disagreement, for the benefit of both parties.”
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – has used the maritime situation as a political cover-up.
