Languages as a subject choice are now valued at the same level as sciences such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics on curriculums for free schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that of the reasons employers stated for having trouble filling a vacancy, 17 percent could be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for a future career.
As more and more job opportunities require language skills, these skills become crucial in a globalized world.
If you have learned a second language, these lifelong skills will bring real benefits in the future, no matter which career you choose.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language a two-digit number of participants (15 percent) could speak.
This is why investing in language learning is now crucial for today’s children.
Knowing more languages, especially those associated with emerging economies, will give children better opportunities to find good jobs.
In Scotland if each school teach in different languages.
Many schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most valuable to the UK on the road towards 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever interests your child, there will always be a selection of languages to choose from in free schools, with teachers who are experts in this field.
Scottish free schools aim to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the knowledge and skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future brings.
It cannot be denied in today’s global business environment that languages are still crucial to the country’s future, and this must be reflected in teaching.
