North Korea will “by no means” agree to unilateral disarmament without confidence
The North Korean foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that continued sanctions strengthened distrust of the United States and that the country would by no means agree to unilaterally release its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual General Assembly that North Korea has taken “significant measures of goodwill” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test area, and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We have not seen a similar response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we have no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to gradual nuclear disarmament, where North Korea is rewarded for gradual disarmament steps, but his statement was significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament completely, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump issued in Singapore on June 12, at the very first meeting between a sitting president of the United States and a North Korean leader, in which Kim promised to work towards “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the Korean War, which lasted from 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first release its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to reduce strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first’, raising pressure via sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposing the ‘declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can put us on our knees is a dream come true for people who don’t know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions create further distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader emphasized in front of the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae over the past five months, adding: “If the other party in this disarmament case were South Korea, rather than the United States, nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have been as trapped as it is.”
The tone of Ris’ speech, however, was very different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that an attack on the mainland United States with North Korea’s missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
After threatening to “completely destroy” North Korea last year, Trump stood in front of the UN this year and praised Kim for being brave enough to take disarmament steps, but said much work remains to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is nuclear disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump saw that he did not have a timeframe for this, saying, “It doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
