Harvard Students Take Courses in Getting Enough Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year will help students get more sleep by tackling the growing unculture of pugging their way through the night with caffeine drinks as fuel.
One academic found that students at the world’s best university often had no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why hasn’t anyone said this before?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains to students how important good sleep habits are for academic and sporting performance, and for the general condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and CEO of the university’s health services, said the university decided to start the course after seeing students suffering from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts for an hour, has a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of a room in a dorm room, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books and learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sporting performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important it is with a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of campus with interactive icons makes participants think about their own daily routine.
“We are aware that this is not going to change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know about this, just as you have a right to know about the risks of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
There is still some pride in being able to pug all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students led to sleep deprivation being a growing problem.
Enough and good sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even as a remedy for weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, leading to constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course. He took one of the classes of the professor last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course inspired him to work for a course that was accessible to the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all master’s students to take a similar study program before enrolling in the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm for when to go to bed as well as for when to get up, and that they should be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic displays and LED lights. This type of light can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep difficulties.
