Johnny English Strikes Again by Rowan Atkinson in Spy Parody
It has become a tradition now to look for Brexit allusions in every new movie with a British oblique look and it seems to be relevant to this revival of the Johnny English action comedy parody franchise – which started in 2003 with Johnny English and resurrected in 2011 with Johnny English Reborn.
Will sarcastic self-satisfaction about how obviously hopeless we are become the nation’s new export commodity?
In any case, the incompetent Johnny English with his bulging eyes and rubber face has had his license renewed to mess it up for the second time – his name says more than anything else that he is a distinct and comic figure intended for territories with non-English-speaking cinema audiences.
He is, of course, the silly secret agent who, despite his bizarre James Bond ambitions, is a mix of Clouseau, a bit of Mr Bean, and a portion of the guy who contributes a single note to the fire truck-themed music entry at the opening ceremony of the London 2012 Olympics.
He is also originally based on the role Atkinson played in the long-forgotten television ads for Barclaycard; the traveler and international mystery man who leaves chaos everywhere.
There are some great moments in the latest Johnny English journey.
I loved how Johnny English approached a helicopter in medieval armor and the rotor blades cut his helmet.
Atkinson’s talent for physical comedy comes to fruition, but the humor feels rather anemic and strangely superfluous, especially now that the “serious” brands like 007 and Mission Impossible are willing to take part in comedy.
The humor seems to be more directed towards children than adults, and to me Johnny English's fades are not as inventive and pointed as the silent film lions in Mr Bean.
The current premise is that the UK is in serious trouble.
A cyber-hacker has infiltrated Britain’s super-secret web network of spies and revealed the identity of all the British agents in the field, to the dismay of the guarding agent – a regrettably small role for Kevin Eldon.
It’s the last drop for a prime minister, a pompous and depressed figure who is already undergoing a complete crisis of political unpopularity: Emma Thompson does a very good job with this sort of Teresa May role, but the script doesn’t give her much to work on.
Her intelligence advisers inform that since every active spy has been revealed, she must bring in some of the retired.
And that means the clumsy Johnny English, who now works as a teacher at a snobby establishment, but unofficially teaches secret intelligence. There are some funny sequences here, when English offers a rock academy for spy activity.
English is snatched back to Whitehall for a quick briefing and reunited with his old, troubled helper Bough, played by Ben Miller.
Bough is now a married man, spliced with a submarine commander, a hysterical upper-class lady role in which Vicki Pepperdine is a bit wasted.
So the Batman and Robin style of messing everything else on queen's mission is back, where they confront Olga Kurylenko's amazing femme fatale, Ophelia Bulletova.
Meanwhile, the prime minister is seduced by the charismatic technology billionaire who claims he can solve Britain’s cyber-problems: the insidious Jason Volta, played by Jake Lacy.
English and Bough begin their journey with a farce: disguised as waiters, they set fire to a flashy French restaurant; they create chaos while hiding aboard Volta’s luxury yacht; and English unleashes pure anarchy as he tries to use a VR headset to make himself known in Volta’s house.
All the stops are really dragged out before the final sequence, but even as gracious and noisy it is, there is a lot that resembles children’s TV with the whole thing.
Pretty mediocre, everything.
And as with the other Johnny English films, I couldn’t help but think: can the British film industry give Rowan Atkinson a role where he can really use his talent?
