What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it contributed to combating poverty?
This Saturday, New York hosts the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event that features an impressive list of stars to perform and an equally impressive mission; eradicating the world’s poverty.
The Global Citizen Festival, now in its seventh year, will make thousands of people flock to the big lawn of Central Park, not only to experience sizes like Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also raise awareness of the event’s real goal of eradicating extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which started in 2012, is a further development of the Global Poverty Project, an international action group that hopes to fight poverty by getting more people to work actively towards poverty.
To get a free ticket to the event (unless one is willing to pay for a VIP ticket), participants had to perform a number of tasks, or “actions,” such as volunteering, sending an email to a world leader, taking a phone call, or in other meaningful ways to raise awareness about their goal of eradicating poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been when there are only 12 years left to achieve the goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a genuine way to get people to fight for change, or just another case of so-called “clicktivism” – that people feel they’re contributing big by signing a petition online or posting a tweet?
Global Citizen says that since 2011, it has recorded more than 19 million “actions” from its supporters, with a wealth of different goals.
They say these actions have helped get world leaders to declare commitments and policies equivalent to more than $37 billion that will improve the situation of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group was able to show up to 390 engagements and announcements as a result of their actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been paid out or collected.
The group estimates that the secured funding so far has had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the main commitments are The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of investors and entrepreneurs based in the UK who are “helping children to exploit their full potential,” and promised to give Rwanda $35 million to help eradicate malnutrition in the country after receiving over 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like you, we can make the social injustice of malnutrition a footnote in history,” Power of Nutrition Ambassador Tracey Ullman told the crowd during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions in the UK to get better nutrition for mothers and children, the government announced funding for a project, Power of Nutrition, which will reach 5 million women and children with nutritional measures.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the website, “what makes you think we can eradicate extreme poverty?”
Global Citizen responded: “It will be a long and difficult road – sometimes we will fall and fail.
But like the important civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed because we stand stronger together.
