“We have to do it now,” he said about the startup.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “personal data warehouse online” or a POD.
It can include contact lists, work lists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available on one browser at the same time.
What is unique about the personal data repository online is that it is entirely up to the user who should have access to that type of information.
The company calls it “personal empowerment through data.”
The idea behind Inrupt is, according to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, that the company should provide the resources, process and relevant expertise to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some contracted developers to work on the project, and a bunch of volunteer programmers.
