National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
New research carried out at a land estate in the Scottish Highlands will uncover how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
There is hope that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and help to design future conservation measures.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brown beetles and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat calls and which species do what.
Subsequently, a habitat map and a report will be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, conservation advisor to the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will be included in the decision on what measures should be introduced, such as grazing and how best to take care of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction work that affects breeding sites and habitat constraints.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road as they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly carry out surveys, surveys of breeding sites, and occasional rescue work.
The organization has also established Scotland's first and only own bat reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have a perfect area for bats,” he says.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of mapping the bats before maintenance is carried out on a property since the unintentional destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young, and perhaps eradicate an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish co-worker for the Bat Conservation Trust, has urged the public to help in the work.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species, we simply don’t know how the populations are doing.”
