Update on algae bloom: Concentrations decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Commission on Fishing and Wildlife (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spotted blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County – suggesting reduced concentrations.
A bloom of red algae stretches about 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots are detected about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported on or off the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Lee County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
There were no reports of airway irritation in northwest Florida last week.
